07451nam a22011055i 9783110670844DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019955787  a97831106708447 a10.1515/97831106708442doi  a(DE-B1597)534431  a(OCoLC)1191864264  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aMermaid Construction :bA Compound-Predicate Construction with Biclausal Appearance /ced. by Tasaku Tsunoda. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XIV, 868 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComparative Handbooks of Linguistics [CHL] ;v600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tList of authors -- tMaps -- tGenetic classification of languages examined or referred to -- t1 Mermaid construction: An introduction and summary -- tI. SOV languages -- t2 Modern Standard Japanese -- t3 Mitsukaido dialect of Japanese -- t4 Old and Early Middle Japanese -- t5 Irabu Ryukyuan -- t6 Korean -- t7 Kolyma Yukaghir -- t8 Sakha (Yakut) -- t9 Khalkha Mongolian -- t10 Amdo Tibetan -- t11 nDrapa -- t12 Kathmandu Newar -- t13 Burmese -- t14 Kurux -- t15 Hindi -- t16 Sidaama -- tII. SVO languages -- t17 Thai -- tIII. VSO/VOS languages -- t18 Tagalog -- tIV Languages in which the order of S, O and V is not fixed -- t19 Koryak -- tIndex of names -- tIndex of languages -- tIndex of subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume provides detailed studies of the crosslinguistically unusual mermaid construction in seventeen languages of Asia, including Modern Standard Japanese, and one language of Africa. This construction appears to be absent in languages of Europe, Oceania and the Americas. The name - mermaid construction - alludes to its paradoxical make-up, where the structure closely resembling a verb-predicate clause ends with what may look like a noun-predicate clause. Superficially it looks biclausal; however, syntactically it is monoclausal. It has a compound predicate which contains an independent noun, a clitic or an affix derived from a noun, or a nominalizer. Its compound predicate has a modal, evidential, aspectual, temporal, stylistic or discourse-related meaning. The paradox is resolved from a diachronic perspective insofar as a biclausal structure is reanalyzed as a monoclausal one. This volume shows how a noun may be reanalyzed to become a constituent of a predicate. It constitutes an important contribution to research on grammaticalization and in particular, the grammaticalization of nouns and more generally, to the typology of syntactic reanalysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aGrammatikalisierung. 4aSubstantiv. 4aZusammengesetztes Prädikat. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aNoun.  a Compound Predicate.  a Grammaticalization.  a Syntactic Reanalysis.1 aEbata, Fuyuki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEbihara, Shiho, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEndo, Fubito, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImamura, Yasunari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatagiri, Masumi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKato, Atsuhiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKawachi, Kazuhiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Joungmin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiryu, Kazuyuki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKobayashi, Masato, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct